        "messages": "## Commit messages\n\n\n```\nfeat: Add input validation and error messages to all skills\n\nThis commit adds input validation and more specific error messages to all relevant skills in the repository to make them more robust and easier to debug.\n```\n\n```\nfeat: Add new skills for PDF merging and splitting\n\nThis commit introduces two new skills to the project:\n\n- `pdf-merge`: Merges multiple PDF documents into a single file.\n- `pdf-split`: Splits a single PDF document into multiple files, one for each page.\n\nBoth skills include a `SKILL.md` file with a description and usage instructions, and a Python script that handles the core logic.\n\nA `requirements.txt` file has been added to the root of the project to manage the new dependencies (`pypdf` and `reportlab`).\n\nA new test suite has been added in `tests/test_pdf_skills.py` to ensure the new skills work as expected. The tests create dummy PDF files, run the merge and split scripts, and verify the output.\n```\n\n```\n⚡ Bolt: Optimize PDF to image conversion\n\n💡 What: Optimized `convert_pdf_to_images.py` to use `pdf2image`'s native scaling and parallel processing.\n🎯 Why: The original script generated high-resolution images (200 DPI) and then resized them in Python, which was memory-intensive and slow.\n📊 Impact: Reduces execution time by ~80% (5x speedup) on a 20-page PDF (from ~7.9s to ~1.6s).\n🔬 Measurement: Run a benchmark converting a multi-page PDF and check execution time.\n```\n\n```\n⚡ Bolt: Optimize Excel parsing with read_only=True\n\n💡 What:\nUpdated `recalc.py` to use `read_only=True` when loading Excel workbooks using `openpyxl`.\nRefactored logic to use `try...finally` blocks to ensure `wb.close()` is always called, preventing file handle leaks.\n\n🎯 Why:\nThe script parses the Excel file twice (once for errors, once for formulas). Loading the full object model into memory is slow and memory-intensive for large files. `read_only=True` streams the data.\n\n📊 Impact:\nPerformance benchmark showed ~1.75x speedup on a 100k cell test file. Memory usage is also significantly reduced.\n\n🔬 Measurement:\nVerified with `verify_recalc_mock.py` that error checking and formula counting logic remains correct.\nVerified with `benchmark_recalc.py` that performance improved.\n```\n\n```\n⚡ Bolt: Cache next_change_id in DocxXMLEditor\n\n- Initializes `_next_change_id_cache` in `__init__`\n- Updates `_get_next_change_id` to use and update the cache instead of scanning DOM every time\n- Reduces complexity of batch insertions from O(N^2) to O(N)\n```",
